Creating frameworks for visualizing and comparing tRFs and miRNAs

Elizabeth Ferrick Kiddie

4/27/2020

Introduction

  • Although every biology student has been taught the well established function of tRNAs as the intermediate decoders from nucleic acid “language” into amino acid “language”, tRNAs are being given a fresh look at their possible roles in other regulatory pathways.

  • With the adoption of widespread RNA sequencing technologies, it’s being appreciated that tRNA sequences are not only existing in the cell as full length mature sequences, but are also accumulating as fragments (Figure 1). These tRNA fragments are a newer class of small RNA fragments that accumulate at predictable sizes with proposed functions currently ranging from miRNA-like gene expression regulation, retrotransposon control, and positive regulation of translational control (Kim 2017, Kuscu 2018, Schorn 2017). The Lambowitz lab is particularly suited to study tRNA fragments, because our thermostable group-II intron reverse transcriptases (TGIRT) can sequence through both full length tRNAs and their fragments simultaneously (Qin 2016). In contrast, conventional RNA sequencing methods struggle sequencing through mature tRNAs, as tRNAs possess substantially stable structure and are heavily decorated with RNA modifications, which together can prevent or lead to early termination of first strand cDNA synthesis (Zheng 2015).



    Figure 1: tRNA fragment processing The mature tRNA secondary structure is centered (with the post-transcriptionally added CCA tail indicated) and surrounded by some of the predominant tRNA fragments that can occur by processing the mature tRNA at different positions (internal fragments and fragments occurring from precursor tRNA are not shown, but may also occur).



  • Although there are nice visualizations of read-mapping available through Integrative Genomics Viewer (IGV) (or through a simpler tool, samtools tview), these tools don’t aggregate the data to give summary data of abundance (Figure 2a). This becomes very problematic when looking at very large datasets, especially when opening a file with IGV without downsampling regularly runs out of memory and personal computers crash when attempting to display the reads of a particular gene, if it is highly represented in the library. Instead, the downsampling option has to be used, which limits the view to a random sample of the reads, and has a coverage track at the top of the viewer to give scale of how prevalent sequences are in the library. This downsampled view can only allow vague conclusions to be made from data, and since it is an aggregate of many different sized reads, the coverage track cannot give reliable abundance estimates of any specific tRNA fragment. There are several tRF databases that use more transparent visualizations of tRNA fragments, tRFdb (tRNA fragment database) and MINTbase (mitochondrial nuclear tRF database). Both of these databases display tRF data as alignments to the tRNA gene, with abundance counts, giving greater clarity of which tRFs are more likely to be biologically relevant (Figure 2b and c). tRFdb only aligns and counts existing tRFs from various large-scale publicly available datasets, whereas MINTbase also includes theoretical fragments, giving unique names to every possible tRF (regardless of if it has been found in a dataset) (Kumar 2015, Pliatsika 2016, Pliatsika 2018). Notable datasets included in MINTbase are tRFs found in datasets from The Cancer Genome Atlas and tRFdb includes tRFs found in argonaut pulldown experiments. One caveat to both databases is that they both only allow for exact matches of the tRF to the tRNA gene, which simplifies the alignments, but might greatly underestimate fragment abundance because tRNA genes have many RNA modifications which can lead to variants introduced during reverse transcription (Qin 2016).

  • So, databases like tRFdb and MINTbase, both contain useful visual outputs for RNA fragment data that I can model a visualization of my own RNA sequencing libraries with. There is one important caveat to tRFdb’s and MINTbase’s methods that I don’t want to mirror, which is that both of these databases only count a tRF read if they are perfect matches. MINTbase even includes links to Modomics (an RNA modification database) (Boccaletto 2018, Dunin-Horkawicz 2006), so you can see just how decorated tRNA sequences are, so it’s not a stretch to assume that possibly a majority of the RNA-seq output will have the presence of modifications, and throwing out these reads could drastically reduce the fragments’ abundance in the data, and therefore it’s assumed importance (Qin 2016).

  • Besides visualizing and counting predominant tRNA fragments, I also want to compare their expression to miRNAs in my RNA-seq libraries. But this is a comparison that is rife with problems, as RNA-seq can do a good job at identifying small RNAs, but not as good of a job at accurately quantifying them.

Aims

1) To make an alignment script so that I can count and align all the tRNA fragment reads from my RNA-seq libraries.

2) Create a scoring method to estimate which miRNAs will be overrepresented versus underrepresented in TGIRT-seq libraries.

Aim 1: tRNA read alignment visualization

In this first aim, I developed a visualization and counting tool for quantifying the most abundant tRNA fragments in my RNA-seq data sets. I wrote a script to visualize the alignment and count the reads in a similar way to several tRNA fragment databases, tRFdb and MINTbase, which align tRNA fragment reads from publicly available datasets and compare the read counts to indicate predominant fragments. With this visualization script, I can now compare my tRNA fragment datasets to other publicly available records more easily, and also have greater confidence in categorizing what the most abundant tRNA fragments in my datasets are.

Python Script

In order to make a python script that could take a reference file and an alignment file to create a visualization of the alignment, it was first important to understand what information I can use from the alignment file (bam file). In my case, the important information contained in the bam file was

1) the reference gene the read aligned to
2) the position where the alignment starts
3) and the sequence of the read.

With these components, I have everything I need to align the reads to the reference.

Click to View the Script 

# This python script takes inputs of a reference sequence and an RNA-seq text file of a specified gene and gives the output of an alignment of the identified reads to it's reference sequence.

# This first input of this script is a fasta formatted reference sequence file and this file is used to generate a dictionary, including the sequence ID as the dictionary key and the sequence as the dictionary value.

refDict = dict()
with open('/Users/elizabethferrick/python/project/Pass1.fa', 'r') as reference:
    refLoS = reference.read().splitlines()
    for i in range(0,len(refLoS),2):
        #print(i)
        refDict[refLoS[i]] = refLoS[i+1]

# The second file input is the RNA sequencing library, which has already been pre-processed on the bash shell to extract the desired columns of data, sort and count them into a list of unique counted sequences, and select for a specified tRNA fragment.

# bash commands for pre-processing RNA-seq bam input file:
# samtools view Pass1_U5.sort.bam | grep 'TRL' | awk '{print $3" "$4" "$10}' | sort | uniq -c | sort -k3 -n | \
#    grep 'TRL-AAG-1-1:TRL-AAG-1-1:tRNA:37:38:63:86' > counted_TRL-AAG-1-1_Pass1_U5.sort.txt

with open('/Users/elizabethferrick/python/project/counted_TRL-AAG-1-1_Pass1_U5.sort.txt','r') as seq:
    seqLoS = seq.read().splitlines()
    seqLoL = []
    for record in seqLoS:
        seqLoL.append(record.split())

# align the sorted pre-processed input file to the reference sequence (called from the dictionary)

align = []
for record in seqLoL:
    record_string = ''
    spacedRead = ''
    if ('>'+record[1]) in refDict:
        spacedRead = ((int(record[2])-1) * '.') + record[3] + \
        ((len(refDict[('>' + record[1])])-(int(record[2]) - 1) - len(record[3])) * '.' + '\t' + record[0])
        align.append(spacedRead)
    record_string = str(('>'+record[1]) +'\n' + refDict[('>'+record[1])] + '\t' + 'reads' + '\n' + '\n'.join(align))

# write the aligned output to a file

with open('U5_TRL-AAG-1-1_align.txt','w') as outFile:
    outFile.write(record_string)

Conclusions

My script is sucessful! There are a few bugs where if a read has an insertion or deletion, it will extend past the reference in the alignment (but this is a minority case since insertions and deletions are rare).

Additional processing on the bash shell with regular expressions allows filtering for just the most abundant reads.

A few improvements can still be made:

  1. Pass in arguments from the bash shell for the input and output file information (whereas right now I’m having to specify the files inside of the script).
  2. Generalize the flow so that more than one output file can be made at a time (right now only one alignment is made at a time).
  3. Add a way to identify the nucleotide variants that are likely RNA modifications.

Aim 2: miRNA scoring in TGIRT-seq libraries

In the second aim, I created a simple scoring method for comparing the 5’ and 3’ end nucleotide biases of the library preparation method I’m using, and I used the scoring method to rank which miRNAs are likely to be excluded from my libraries. This was accomplished by taking the Fastqc per base sequence content for all the reads of a miRNA library composed of equal abundance of 962 synthetic miRNAs (prepared as 3 replicates), and converting the biased percentage composition at the first and last 3 base positions into a score, representing if the nucleotide is favored or unfavored at each position. This scoring method was then iterated over the miRNA sequences in the library in order to give a predictive score of whether the miRNA has a favorable or unfavorable sequence, given the bias for library preparation. This predicted favorability score was compared to the observed expression in the RNA-seq dataset. I also used the scoring method to determine a favorability score for tRNA fragment sequences compared to miRNAs and saw that the bias of the RT does favor tRNA fragment sequences over some miRNA sequences.

Bash Script

This first bash script was used to process the raw data with Fastqc and extract the Per base sequence content.

Click for fastqc_processing_Perbase.sh

 #!/bin/bash
 
 # the purpose of this script is to take a deep seq file with extension .fq.gz, run it through fastqc, unzip only the text file, and extract the Per base sequence content from the txt file
 
# original file input:
## filename.fq.gz (can be entered as bash wildcard *.fq.gz)
 
# so final files created:
## filename_fastqc.zip
## filename_fastqc.html 
## filename_fastqc_data.txt
## filename_fastqc_PerBaseSeqContent.txt
 
module load fastqc
 
# "$#" allows extended inputs from the shell
# so I can use bash wildcards to process many files at a time
for filenameExt in "$@"; do
 
# filename is the filename WITHOUT extensions, extracted using parameter expansions
   filename=${filenameExt%.fq.gz}
 
# first step runs the file through fastqc
# the output of the command below are filename_fastqc.html and filename_fastqc.zip 
   fastqc ${filename}.fq.gz 
 
# the next step is to unzip the fastqc_data.txt file inside filename_fastqc.zip
# the structure of the path to the txt file can be checked with less filename_fastqc.zip or unzip -l filename_fastqc.zip
# redirecting stdout to a file allows renaming the data file with the desired specific filename
   unzip -p ${filename}_fastqc.zip ${filename}_fastqc/fastqc_data.txt > ${filename}_fastqc_data.txt
 
# extract just the per base sequence content from the fastqc_data.txt file

   sed -n '/>>Per base sequence content/{:a;n;/>>END_MODULE/q;p;ba}' ${filename}_fastqc_data.txt > ${filename}_fastqc_PerBaseSeqContent.txt
 
done

Python Scripts

This first python script was used to evaluate the scoring method that was calculated in the first part of the R script, iterating the score associated with each of the first and last 3 nucleotides of each miRNA sequence.

Click for miRNA_scoring.py

# bring in the data and do processing steps to convert it into a list of lists
seqLoL = []
with open('/Users/elizabethferrick/Box Sync/lab/deep_seq/miRNA/MiR.info', 'r') as inFile:
    seqLoS = inFile.read().splitlines()
    for record in seqLoS:
        seqLoL.append(record.split())
seqLoL.pop(0)

scoreLoL = []
with open('/Users/elizabethferrick/Box Sync/lab/deep_seq/miRNA/scoring_PerBaseSeqContent.txt', 'r') as inFile2:
    scoreLoS = inFile2.read().splitlines()
    for record in scoreLoS:
        scoreLoL.append(record.split())
scoreLoL.pop(0)

# create the dictionary of the scores reading the info from scoreLoL
# line[0] = base = key
# line[1] = index = index in List of dictionaries
# line[2] = score = value
scoreDict = []
for i in range(0,6):
    scoreDict.append({'A':0, 'T':0, 'G':0, 'C':0})
for line in scoreLoL:
    scoreDict[int(line[1])][line[0]] += int(line[2])

# evaluate the scores stored in the dictionary for each of the miRxplore miRNAs

evalScoreList = []
for line in seqLoL:
    evalScore = 0
    for i in range(-3,3):
        evalScore += scoreDict[i][line[1][i]]
    evalScoreList.append(evalScore)

with open('miRxplore_scored_list.txt', 'w') as outFile:
    outFile.write('ID' + '\t' + 'Score' + '\n')
    for i in range(len(seqLoL)):
        outFile.write(seqLoL[i][0] + '\t' + str(evalScoreList[i]) + '\n')

Conclusions

All my scripts successfully give the output that I was looking for. But, the scoring system is not very predictive…it’s only got a 15% correlation with the expression data. However, I did compare the scores for the lowest expressing miRNAs to the predictive scores for tRNA fragments sequences, and it did accurately predict the comparison in expression, that the miRNA had a very low score, whereas the tRNA fragment had a high score. So even though the scoring is primitive, I think it still is a good start for understanding the biases for detection in RNA-seq.

Many improvements can be made:

  1. Make the scoring wider range to differentiate the ranks more (multiple the fraction by a number before rounding).
  2. Score based on first and last 4nt or 5nt, instead of just 3.
  3. Add additional sequences to compare against (like full length tRNAs).
  4. Perhaps figure a way to classify miRNAs into groups of overexpressing and underexpressing and look for motif similarities?
